LeetCode 12 and LeetCode 13 are reverse problems that work on the same Roman numeral system but require opposite thinking approaches.
In Roman to Integer (13), the task is to read a Roman numeral string and calculate its numeric value,
so the main idea is to scan the string from left to right and compare each character with the next character to decide whether to add
or subtract its value; if a smaller numeral appears before a larger numeral, it means subtraction (like IV = 4 or IX = 9),
otherwise we add the value, which makes this problem a reading and comparison-based logic where we decode the Roman structure by 
observing relationships between symbols. On the other hand, Integer to Roman (12) requires building a Roman numeral from a given number,
so instead of comparing characters, we use a greedy approach where we always pick the largest possible Roman value that fits into the number
and subtract it while adding its corresponding symbol to the result, repeating this process until the number becomes zero;
this ensures that the Roman numeral is formed correctly in descending order (like 1994 → 1000 + 900 + 90 + 4 → MCMXCIV).
The key difference is that problem 13 focuses on analyzing and interpreting the Roman numeral by checking symbol relationships,
while problem 12 focuses on constructing the Roman numeral by repeatedly selecting the largest valid symbol,
meaning one problem decodes the system and the other encodes the system. Both problems run in linear or constant time and rely on the 
same Roman value mapping, but the mental model is different: Roman to Integer requires comparison and decision-making at each step, 
while Integer to Roman requires greedy selection and subtraction at each step, so remembering this as “13 reads and calculates, 
while 12 builds and subtracts” makes it easy to recall even after a long time.
  
